cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use this method or the error-step locator, please cite it."
title: "Shared Blind Spot vs Self-Preference: a method for separating shared reasoning failure from familiarity in LLM-as-a-judge"
authors:
  - family-names: "Ning"
    given-names: "Charl"
    email: "charlcc07@gmail.com"
date-released: "2026-06-26"
license: MIT
repository-code: "https://github.com/charlnoc/shared-blind-spot-vs-self-preference"
url: "https://github.com/charlnoc/shared-blind-spot-vs-self-preference"
keywords:
  - LLM-as-a-judge
  - self-preference bias
  - chain-of-thought
  - error localization
  - evaluation
abstract: >
  A reproducible protocol and a mechanical, model-free error-step locator for
  distinguishing two causes of same-family false endorsement in LLM judges:
  surface familiarity (self-preference) versus a shared blind spot, where the
  judge fails to catch an error because its own reasoning fails at the same step.
  The protocol operationalises the split via a shared-error rate against a chance
  baseline with a perplexity control; the locator re-executes reasoning steps
  rather than asking an LLM, avoiding contamination by the bias under study.
